{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"name":"ir","display_name":"R","language":"R"},"language_info":{"name":"R","codemirror_mode":"r","pygments_lexer":"r","mimetype":"text/x-r-source","file_extension":".r","version":"4.0.5"}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"source":"<a href=\"https://www.kaggle.com/code/robynp02/capstone-project?scriptVersionId=145348860\" target=\"_blank\"><img align=\"left\" alt=\"Kaggle\" title=\"Open in Kaggle\" src=\"https://kaggle.com/static/images/open-in-kaggle.svg\"></a>","metadata":{},"cell_type":"markdown"},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# **Introduction**\n\nIn this capstone study for the Google Analytics certificate, we are tasked with studying data from the fictional company [Bellabeat](https://bellabeat.com/).\n\n### **About the company**\n\nUrška Sršen and Sando Mur founded Bellabeat, a high-tech company that manufactures health-focused smart products. Sršen used her background as an artist to develop beautifully designed technology that informs and inspires women around the world. Collecting data on activity, sleep, stress, and reproductive health has allowed Bellabeat to empower women with knowledge about their own health and habits. Since it was founded in 2013, Bellabeat has grown rapidly and quickly positioned itself as a tech-driven wellness company for women.\n\nBy 2016, Bellabeat had opened offices around the world and launched multiple products. Bellabeat products became available through a growing number of online retailers in addition to their own e-commerce channel on their website. The company has invested in traditional advertising media, such as radio, out-of-home billboards, print, and television, but focuses on digital marketing extensively. Bellabeat invests year-round in Google Search, maintaining active Facebook and Instagram pages, and consistently engages consumers on Twitter. Additionally, Bellabeat runs video ads on Youtube and display ads on the Google Display Network to support campaigns around key marketing dates.\n\n# Business Task\n\nSršen knows that an analysis of Bellabeat's available consumer data would reveal more opportunities for growth. She has asked the marketing analytics team to focus on a Bellabeat product and analyze smart device usage data in order to gain insight into how people are already using their smart devices. Then, using this information, she would like high-level recommendations for how these trends can inform Bellabeat marketing strategy.\n\nThere are three important questions that Urška Sršen is asking to be considered:\n\n1.  What are some trends in smart device usage?\n\n2.  How could these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?\n\n3.  How could these trends help influence Bellabeat marketing strategy?\n\n# Source\n\nThe original data comes from [FitBit Fitness Tracker Data](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/arashnic/fitbit) (CC0: Public Domain, dataset made available through Mobius): This Kaggle data set contains personal fitness tracker from thirty fitbit users. Thirty eligible Fitbit users consented to the submission of personal tracker data, including minute-level output for physical activity, heart rate, and sleep monitoring. It includes information about daily activity, steps, and heart rate that can be used to explore users' habits.\n\n# Preparation\n\nThere are 18 total files:\n\n-   dailyActivity_merged.csv\n-   dailyCalories_merged.csv\n-   dailyIntensities_merged.csv\n-   dailySteps_merged.csv\n-   heartrate_seconds_merged.csv\n-   hourlyCalories_merged.csv\n-   hourlyIntensities_merged.csv\n-   hourlySteps_merged.csv\n-   minuteCaloriesNarrow_merged.csv\n-   minuteCaloriesWide_merged.csv\n-   minuteIntensitiesNarrow_merged.csv\n-   minuteIntensitiesWide_merged.csv\n-   minuteCaloriesNarrow_merged.csv\n-   minuteSleep_merged.csv\n-   minuteStepsNarrow_merged.csv\n-   minuteStepsWide_merged.csv\n-   sleepDay_merged.csv weightLogInfo_merged.csv\n\n### Pre-Cleaning\n\nThe data was all first loaded into and quickly examined using Google Sheets. I used the function COUNTUNIQUE to determine the exact number of participants in each dataset.\n\nSince 'dailyActivity_merged' already contains all of the same information as 'dailyCalories_merged', 'dailyIntensities_merged', and 'dailySteps_merged', only 'dailyActivity_merged' will be used.\n\nThere is not enough information to consider any overall trends by the minute as there is only narrow calorie data, so it will not be used. Similarly, weight log info only contains data from eight unique participants, therefore it can also be excluded in this analysis as the small sample may skew the results one way or another.\n\nLikewise, daily sleep does not include the same number of participants (there are only 24 compared to the 33 in the 'hourly' and 'daily' datasets) as the 'hourly' and 'daily activity' logs and may taint the results of the analysis.\n\nFor the hourly data, 'hourlyCalories_merged', 'hourlyIntensities_merged and 'hourlySteps_merged' all contained the exact same ID and Activity Date information. These were small enough sets that this could be done manually without any extra effort. I combined the step total from 'hourlySteps_merged' and intensity columns from 'hourlyIntensities_merged' into the spreadsheet 'hourlyCalories_merged' using the IMPORTRANGE function.\n\nI have retained unaltered copies of the original data on my computer if needed for further analysis.\n\n### Libraries\n\nThe following libraries were loaded to help with analysis.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"library(tidyverse)\nlibrary(dplyr)\nlibrary(tidyr)\nlibrary(skimr)\nlibrary(janitor)\nlibrary(here)\nlibrary(ggplot2)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-10-04T21:01:48.989695Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-10-04T21:01:48.992224Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.020406Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Methodology - Part 1\n\nWith the packages and libraries loaded, I can now begin cleansing and analysis.\n\n### Daily Average\n\nBefore starting analysis, I decided to rename the data frames to something easier to work with. And while not necessary, for sake of ease and consistency, I made the column names all lower case.\n\nNext, I want to find out the average of all measurable columns (i.e. TotalSteps, TotalDistance, etc). First I'll start with the 'dailyActivity_merged' data set, or as I've called it, 'd2'.\n\nSince there are 30 unique participants, I wanted to find the daily average per user but also of the users as a whole group. I aggregated the individuals and rounded down to 2 decimal spots for readability.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"d2 <- read.csv('/kaggle/input/capstonedata/dailyActivity_merged.csv')\nnames(d2) <- tolower(names(d2))\navgdaily <- aggregate(d2[,3:15], list(d2$id), mean)\nrd2 <- round(avgdaily, digits=2)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.023749Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.025678Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.075164Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Below is a table previewing the top-10 results sorted by total steps in descending order.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<p>\n<table>\n   \n<colgroup>\n<col style=\"width: 7%\" />\n<col style=\"width: 7%\" />\n<col style=\"width: 7%\" />\n<col style=\"width: 7%\" />\n<col style=\"width: 7%\" />\n<col style=\"width: 7%\" />\n<col style=\"width: 7%\" />\n<col style=\"width: 7%\" />\n<col style=\"width: 7%\" />\n<col style=\"width: 7%\" />\n<col style=\"width: 7%\" />\n<col style=\"width: 7%\" />\n<col style=\"width: 7%\" />\n<col style=\"width: 7%\" />\n</colgroup>\n<tbody>\n<tr class=\"odd\">\n<td><p><strong>participant id number</strong></p></td>\n<td><p><strong>total<br />\nsteps</strong></p></td>\n<td><p><strong>total<br />\ndistance</strong></p></td>\n<td><p><strong>tracker<br />\ndistance</strong></p></td>\n<td><p><st