5</p></td>\n<td><p>143.84</p></td>\n<td><p>850.45</p></td>\n<td><p>2566.35</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n*To view the full table, see **Appendix - Average Total Steps**.*\n\nBased on total steps, it looks like the users were generally pretty active every day. But to be sure, I also looked at the sedentary minutes by user.\n\n*To view the full table, see **Appendix - Average Sedentary Minutes***.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"dlyrnd <- select(rd2,Group.1,sedentaryminutes)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.07818Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.07979Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.099581Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"This table below shows the top-10 participants who had the most sedentary minutes on average along with their total steps, sorted in descending order by sedentary minutes.\n\n\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<style type=\"text/css\">\n.tg  {border-collapse:collapse;border-spacing:0;}\n.tg td{border-color:black;border-style:solid;border-width:1px;font-family:Arial, sans-serif;font-size:14px;\n  overflow:hidden;padding:10px 5px;word-break:normal;}\n.tg th{border-color:black;border-style:solid;border-width:1px;font-family:Arial, sans-serif;font-size:14px;\n  font-weight:normal;overflow:hidden;padding:10px 5px;word-break:normal;}\n.tg .tg-0pky{border-color:inherit;text-align:left;vertical-align:top}\n</style>\n<table class=\"tg\">\n<thead>\n  <tr>\n    <th class=\"tg-0pky\">participant ID number</th>\n    <th class=\"tg-0pky\">sedentary minutes</th>\n    <th class=\"tg-0pky\">total steps</th>\n  </tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n  <tr>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">1927972279</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">1317.42</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">916.13</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">6775888955</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">1299.42</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">2,519.69</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">8253242879</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">1287.37</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">6,482.16</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">8583815059</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">1267.23</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">7,198.52</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">1624580081</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">1257.74</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">5,743.90</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">4020332650</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">1237.26</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">2,267.23</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">2320127002</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">1220.1</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">4,716.87</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">4057192912</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">1217.25</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">3,838.00</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">1844505072</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">1206.61</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">2,580.06</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">6290855005</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">1193.03</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-0pky\">5,649.55</td>\n  </tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Clearly there is a correlation between average steps and sedentary time as users with the most steps had the least sedentary minutes.\n\n### Group Average\n\nNext, I looked at what their activity was like as a unit. I don't need the ID or Activity Date columns, so I dropped them and made a new table called 'daily2.' Now I can properly examine the averages of the remaining columns.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"daily2 <- d2[-c(1, 2)]\navgdaily2 <- sapply(X=daily2, FUN = mean, rm.na=TRUE)\nrndavg <- round(avgdaily2, digits = 2)\nhead(rndavg)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.102636Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.10425Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.131498Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"As a group, they most notably had nearly 1000 sedentary minutes and walked 7600 steps, which lets us know that the users were likely fairly inactive throughout the day.\n\n### Daily Maximum\n\n### Daily Individual\n\nNow I want to look at the maximum activity of each participant.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"maxdly <- aggregate(d2[,3:15], list(d2$id), max)\ncolnames(maxdly)[1]='id'\nhead(maxdly[order(maxdly$totalsteps, decreasing=TRUE),])","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.135174Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.137598Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.187425Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"That sums up the individual averages.\n\n### Analaysis - Part 1: Daily Activity\n\nBy examining the average, it's easy to get a big picture idea of how often participants were moving every day. User 8877689391 walked the most steps on average with 16040 steps taken daily over the course of the two months from which the data was captured. As a whole, the 30 participants walked nearly 7638 steps each day. Based on this, it seems like each user was pretty active throughout the course of the day.\n\nBut, the sedentary minutes give us a different picture. User 1927972279 was sedentary on average for 1317 minutes. As a group, the participants were sedentary for 991 minutes. This indicates that the FitBit users from this study are not very active throughout the day.\n\n\"Active minutes\" are not defined so it's hard to say what that means. But, when combining sedentary minutes and steps, it seems that users are probably getting steps in through typical daily activity (i.e. running errands) without necessarily exercising. Examining the hourly and intensity data can give better insight to this.\n\n# Methodology - Part 2\n\nThe hourly information gives a more detailed snapshot than the daily data. It can help determine if my earlier conclusions were correct.\n\n## Hourly Average\n\n### Individual Average\n\nThe methodology will follow largely the same pattern as it did with the daily data.\n\nFirst things first, I'll start by renaming the data and making all the column names lowercase.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"hrly <- read.csv('/kaggle/input/capstonedata/hourlyCalories_merged1.csv')\nnames(hrly) <- tolower(names(hrly))","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.191562Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.193237Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.300515Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Next it's important to check out the structure of this data.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"str(hrly)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.303434Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.304945Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.335039Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"The 'id', 'activityhour', and 'calories' columns are all 'characters', which means that they're letters only and cannot be parsed as numbers, so the data will need to undergo transformation. The first step is to drop 'activityhour' as it's not needed for this analysis.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"hz <- hrly[,c(-2)]","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.338032Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.339582Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.353259Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Then, columns 1 and 2 will need to be converted to numeric type data. And since this data set contains zeroes, which are actually important to our findings, but are not yet recognized by R, that will also be transformed.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"hz2 <- replace(hz, is.na(hz), 0)\n#r transform_id\nhz3 <- transform(hz2,id = as.numeric(id))\n#r transform_cals\nhz4 <- transform(hz3,calories = as.numeric(calories))\n#r replace_NAs_again\nh5 <- replace(hz4, is.na(hz4), 0)\n#r hourly_aggregate\nhzavg <- aggregate(h5[,2:5],by=list(h5$id),FUN=mean, na.rm=TRUE)\n#r drop_row1_only0\nhzavg2 <- hzavg[-1,]\ncolnames(hzavg2)[1]='id'\nhead(hzavg2)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.356128Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.357663Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.589462Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Now that the data has been cleaned and transformed, we can look at hourly averages for the individuals.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"hrag <- aggregate(hzavg2[,2:5], list(hzavg2$id), mean)\nhrag2 <- round(hrag, digits=2)\ncolnames(hrag2)[1]='id'\nhead(hrag2[order(hrag2$steptotal, decreasing=TRUE),])","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.592423Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.594731Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.632115Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Since we don't have sedentary minutes by hour, the only two columns that can be compared are calories and the total amount of steps users took. However, calorie burn rate will vary greatly by person[^1] based on myriad of factors so the best data to use are steps.\n\n[^1]: [Mayo Clinic](https://www.mayoclinic.org/healthy-lifestyle/weight-loss/in-depth/metabolism/art-20046508)\n\n### Group Average\n\nMoving on to the group as a whole, similar steps will be repeated here as they were for the daily data above. Once again, ID and Activity Date columns are not relevant to this analysis and were discarded to make a new data frame.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"hrlygrp <- hzavg2[,-c(1)]\nhrlygrp2 <- sapply(X=hrlygrp, FUN = mean, rm.na=TRUE)\nround(hrlygrp2, digits = 2)\nrndhrly <- round(hrlygrp2, digits = 2)","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.63511Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.636734Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.669044Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Great, now we have the average steps all 30 participants took every hour. Now let's look at the maximum for each individual.\n\n### Hourly Maximum\n\nSince we looked at the individual daily maximum, it's helpful to repeat the same steps for hourly maximum.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"hrlymax <- aggregate(h5[,2:5], list(h5$id), max)\ncolnames(hrlymax)[1]='id'\nhrmax <- hrlymax[-c(1),]","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.671926Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.673404Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.781849Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<table>\n<thead>\n  <tr>\n    <th>participant id number</th>\n    <th>step total</th>\n    <th>total intensity</th>\n    <th>average intensity</th>\n    <th>calories</th>\n  </tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n  <tr>\n    <td>8877689391</td>\n    <td>337.16</td>\n    <td>9.54</td>\n    <td>0.16</td>\n    <td>409.09</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>8053475328</td>\n    <td>311.2</td>\n    <td>8.97</td>\n    <td>0.15</td>\n    <td>373.31</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>1503960366</td>\n    <td>261.19</td>\n    <td>8.09</td>\n    <td>0.13</td>\n    <td>300.44</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>7007744171</td>\n    <td>244.93</td>\n    <td>8.79</td>\n    <td>0.15</td>\n    <td>299.95</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>2022484408</td>\n    <td>238.93</td>\n    <td>8.52</td>\n    <td>0.14</td>\n    <td>291.67</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>3977333714</td>\n    <td>235.81</td>\n    <td>7.61</td>\n    <td>0.13</td>\n    <td>268.35</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>4388161847</td>\n    <td>217.53</td>\n    <td>7.16</td>\n    <td>0.12</td>\n    <td>281.59</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>6962181067</td>\n    <td>207.39</td>\n    <td>7.44</td>\n    <td>0.12</td>\n    <td>249.37</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>2347167796</td>\n    <td>206.93</td>\n    <td>7.26</td>\n    <td>0.12</td>\n    <td>251.29</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>7086361926</td>\n    <td>196.11</td>\n    <td>6.78</td>\n    <td>0.11</td>\n    <td>250.23</td>\n  </tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"*To view the full table, see **Appendix - Hourly Individual Max***.*","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"With the highest individual hourly step being only a little more than 3000 (\\~50 steps per hour), this doesn't seem to indicate anyone who is exercising vigorously--or at least for a long time. On average, it takes about 2100 steps to walk a mile[^2]. So these users aren't going for distance or (probably) time.\n\n[^2]: **USA Today - How many steps are in a mile?**\\\n    <https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/health-wellness/2022/06/20/number-of-steps-in-a-mile/7647804001/>\n    \n\n## Visualization","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"The scatter plot below shows data from the individual daily average sorted by ID (as called \"Group.1\" here) and with total steps representing the Y axis. Calories burned are shaded in blue.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"ggplot(data=rd2) +\ngeom_point(mapping=aes(x=Group.1, y=totalsteps, color = calories)) ","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.784928Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-10-04T21:01:49.786602Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-10-04T21:01:50.079173Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Similar to the plot above, this graph shows the individual max daily sorted by ID on the X-axis and total steps on the Y-axis.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"ggplot(data=maxdly) +\ngeom_point(mapping=aes(x=id, y=totalsteps, color=calories))","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2023-10-04T21:01:50.084128Z","iopub.execute_input":"2023-10-04T21:01:50.085733Z","iopub.status.idle":"2023-10-04T21:01:50.382198Z"},"trusted":true},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Conclusion\n\nUrška Sršen requested these three questions be kept in mind during analysis:\n\n1.  **What are some trends in smart device usage?**\n\n-   Users were fairly sedentary throughout the day, even if they were accomplishing the majority of their \"exercise\" through typical daily routine. Step totals ranged from 337.16 at the high end to 19.29 at the low end on average per hour. Cumulatively, users managed between 916 and 16040 steps on average per day. As a group, the users completed 7637.91 steps daily and 160.08 hourly.\n\n-   Given how many steps some users managed to get in some days, they're likely not engaging in conscious, purposeful exercise except once per day.\n\n2.  **How could these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?**\n\n-   Bellabeat already has a fantastic product that can help users with goal setting and stress management. But sometimes people need a push. With Bellabeat's bio-response tracking, users can get even more in tuned with their bodies through helpful reminders on their watch or on the app that can encourage users to move more throughout the day and achieve their goals.\n\n3.  **How could these trends help influence Bellabeat marketing strategy?**\n\n-   The [Center for Disease Control recommends](https://www.cdc.gov/physicalactivity/basics/adults/index.htm) at least \"150 minutes of moderate-intensity physical activity\" each week. Push notifications are a great way to remind users to get up and get moving. Targeted exercises can change with how well users are or are not meeting their goals and premium users can tap intoeven more personalized coaching with awareness of how much more exercise they're getting. With menstrual cycle and heart rate tracking, push notifications can be helpful reminders to get blood flowing, which can improve mood and overall physical health.\n\n# Appendix\n\n## Tables\n\n#### **Average Total Steps**","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"<table>\n<thead>\n  <tr>\n    <th>participant ID number</th>\n    <th>total steps</th>\n    <th>total distance</th>\n    <th>tracker distance</th>\n    <th>logged activities distance</th>\n    <th>very active distance</th>\n    <th>moderatelyactive distance</th>\n    <th>light active distance</th>\n    <th>sedentary<br>active distance</th>\n    <th>very active mins</th>\n    <th>fairly active mins</th>\n    <th>lightly active mins</th>\n    <th>sedentary<br>mins</th>\n    <th>calories</th>\n  </tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n  <tr>\n    <td>8877689391</td>\n    <td>16040.03</td>\n    <td>13.21</td>\n    <td>13.21</td>\n    <td>0</td>\n    <td>6.64</td>\n    <td>0.34</td>\n    <td>6.19</td>\n    <td>0.01</td>\n    <td>66.06</td>\n    <td>9.94</td>\n    <td>234.71</td>\n    <td>1112.87</td>\n    <td>3420.26</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>8053475328</td>\n    <td>14763.29</td>\n    <td>11.48</td>\n    <td>11.48</td>\n    <td>0</td>\n    <td>8.51</td>\n    <td>0.42</td>\n    <td>2.53</td>\n    <td>0</td>\n    <td>85.16</td>\n    <td>9.58</td>\n    <td>150.97</td>\n    <td>1148</td>\n    <td>2945.81</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>1503960366</td>\n    <td>12116.74</td>\n    <td>7.81</td>\n    <td>7.81</td>\n    <td>0</td>\n    <td>2.86</td>\n    <td>0.79</td>\n    <td>4.15</td>\n    <td>0</td>\n    <td>38.71</td>\n    <td>19.16</td>\n    <td>219.94</td>\n    <td>848.16</td>\n    <td>1816.42</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>2022484408</td>\n    <td>11370.65</td>\n    <td>8.08</td>\n    <td>8.08</td>\n    <td>0</td>\n    <td>2.42</td>\n    <td>0.72</td>\n    <td>4.94</td>\n    <td>0</td>\n    <td>36.29</td>\n    <td>19.35</td>\n    <td>257.45</td>\n    <td>1112.58</td>\n    <td>2509.97</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td>7007744171</td>\n    <td>11323.42</td>\n    <td>8.02</td>\n    <td>7.58</td>\n    <td>2.12</td>\n    <td>2.41</td>\n  